### Optional OpenStreetMap / Leaflet Integration
We also provide an optional OpenStreetMap‑based map implementation using **Leaflet**. The UI can be switched to this provider via a simple toggle in the header. All core features (marker placement, routing, vehicle telemetry) work identically; only the basemap source changes. To enable it, include the Leaflet CSS/JS assets and set the `mapProvider` variable to "leaflet" in `index.html`. This is optional and does not affect the existing Google Maps setup.

#### OpenStreetMap / Leaflet API Overview

| Component | Availability | Typical Usage |
|-----------|--------------|---------------|
| **OpenStreetMap tile server** | Public raster tile endpoint (`https://{s}.tile.openstreetmap.org/{z}/{x}/{y}.png`) | Use as `L.tileLayer` source in Leaflet. No API key required, respect fair‑use limits. |
| **Overpass API** | Read‑only query API for OSM vector data | Fetch POIs, roads, etc., via custom queries; return GeoJSON that can be added to Leaflet. |
| **Nominatim geocoder** | Free address ↔︎ coordinate service (`https://nominatim.openstreetmap.org/search?...`) | Implement address lookup in UI; rate‑limited (~1 req / sec). |
| **Routing services** | External services built on OSM data (OpenRouteService, OSRM, GraphHopper) | Request route polyline JSON and display via `L.polyline`. Requires separate API keys or self‑hosted instance. |
| **Leaflet library** | Pure JavaScript map renderer (≈ 30 KB) | Handles pan/zoom, marker placement, layers, and interaction entirely client‑side. |

All of these APIs are **optional** and can be mixed with the existing Google Maps integration. Simply replace the tile layer source and, if needed, add calls to Overpass/Nominatim for search and routing features.

